<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="102" pageId="5" pageNumber="100" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="100">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="101" pageId="5" pageNumber="100">
A previous collection of this species, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="100">X.P. Vu</emphasis>
et al. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="100">HNK 58</emphasis>
, K!, had been identified as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Oreocharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oreocharis hirsuta" order="Passeriformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="100">Oreocharis hirsuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species from Thailand that demarcates the southern 
<pageBreakToken pageId="6" pageNumber="101" start="start">most</pageBreakToken>
distribution of the genus (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/4109363" author="Barnett, EC" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" pagination="249 - 259" refId="B1" refString="Barnett, EC, 1961. Contributions to the flora of Thailand: LV. Kew Bulletin 15: 249 - 259, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/4109363" title="Contributions to the flora of Thailand: LV." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/4109363" volume="15" year="1961">Barnett 1961</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.23.1.1" author="Moeller, M" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" pagination="1 - 36" refId="B11" refString="Moeller, M, Middleton, DJ, Nishii, K, Wei, YG, Sontag, S, Weber, A, 2011. A new delineation for Oreocharis incorporating an additional ten genera of Chinese Gesneriaceae. Phytotaxa 23: 1 - 36, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.23.1.1" title="A new delineation for Oreocharis incorporating an additional ten genera of Chinese Gesneriaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.23.1.1" volume="23" year="2011">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Möller">Moeller</normalizedToken>
et al. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
). When comparing the specimens studied here with type material and recent collections of 
<taxonomicName genus="O." lsidName="O. hirsuta" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="hirsuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">O. hirsuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the herbaria of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew (K) and the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh (E), it was found that they can be morphologically differentiated (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Morphological comparison between Oreocharis longituba sp. nov. and O. hirsuta Barnett." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/3BE6B3D7C1E3F92FF485D1FB0D3E81E1" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" tableUuid="3BE6B3D7C1E3F92FF485D1FB0D3E81E1">2</tableCitation>
; Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Oreocharis longituba W. H. Chen, Q. H. Nguyen &amp; Y. M. Shui, sp. nov. (A-H) and its most similar species, Oreocharis hirsuta Barnett (I-L) A Habitat B Mature plant C Abaxial leaf surface D, E Front view of flower F Pistil with immature stigma, disc and calyx G Lateral view of flower H Opened corolla I Mature plant J Flower and fruits K Front view of flowers L Side view of flowers. Scale bars: A, I = 5 cm, D-H = 1 cm; J, K, L = 2 cm. A-H photographs by Yu-Min Shui, I-L by Preecha Karaket of Middleton et al. 4550." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.94.21329.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/182230" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">2I-L</figureCitation>
). Earlier collections by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pételot">Petelot</normalizedToken>
and Poilane in Vietnam and deposited in the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Muséum">Museum</normalizedToken>
National 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’Histoire">d'Histoire</normalizedToken>
Naturelle in Paris (P), remained unnamed until now. These collections were made near Chapa at Lo Qui Ho, a station on the slopes near the summit of Fan Si Pan).
</paragraph>
